{"questionId":"27687","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following table shows the Mathematics test scores <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and the Science test scores <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;for a group of eight students.</p>\n<p><img src=\"__IMG__/ae3cd62eb16ff220585a667f22678d7489460e65.png\"></p>\n<p>The regression line of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math> on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> for this data can be written in the form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Write down the value of the Pearson’s product-moment correlation coefficient, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>981464</mn><mo>…</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>981</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> A common error is to enter the data incorrectly into the GDC, and obtain the answers&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01700</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>09814</mn><mo>…</mo></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>980888</mn><mo>…</mo></math> Some candidates may write the 3 sf answers, ie.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>10</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>981</mn></math> or 2 sf answers, ie.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>98</mn></math>. In these cases award <em><strong>A0A0</strong></em> for part (a) and <em><strong>A0</strong></em> for part (b). Even though some values round to an accepted answer, they come from incorrect working.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27687","referenceCode":"22N.2.SL.TZ0.1b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Write down the value of the Pearson’s product-moment correlation coefficient, r.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.4—Pearsons, scatter diagrams, eqn of y on x"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}